A large testsuite of different simulations. Can generate both closed-packed lattice, poisson distributed or glass generated ICs. The glass generation occurs through an IC-generator that can produce glass for a wide-range of density profiles.

Before starting, you need to change GASOLINE_DIR, CHANGA_DIR, SPHEXA_DIR variables in runtest.sh to point towards your specific gasoline/changa/sphexa build and if you are running serial mpi etc. :
default is:

If you wanna use the glass relaxation (hacked version of gasoline) you need to go into icgenerator/mdl/mpi and make and icgenerator/gasoline/ and make mpi (for default)

Usage: ./runtest.sh [-i] [-r] [-a value1] ... [-h value8] <nameofsimulation> <Nsmooth> <Nres> <0: lattice | 1: rand | 2: glass>

Options:
  -a, -b, -c, ...    These options depend on the simulation. To see the specific options, enter the nameofsimulation without arguments.
  -i                 Interactive.
  -r                 After the simulation finishes, run the matching analysis
                     (setupfiles/IC_analysis_<simulation>.py) with --save-reference
                     to bless a regression baseline for the run (see "Analysis"
                     below). Silently skipped if no analysis script exists.

Arguments:
  nameofsimulation   Name of the simulation to be run (e.g., shocktube).
  Nsmooth            Number of neigbours within smoothing kernel
  Nres               Resolution for the simulation.
  0 | 1 | 2          Initial conditions type:
                     0: lattice
                     1: random
                     2: glass
If glass data file exist for a specific Nsmooth it will skipp the glass generation and run the simulation. If you choose an nSmooth that does not have a glass datafile it will do the whole glass generation again.

List of available simulations:
(enter a name without arguments to see its specific -a..-h options.
 [A] = has a post-processing analysis script, setupfiles/IC_analysis_<name>.py)

  Hydrodynamics:
    kh            [A]  Kelvin-Helmholtz instability (linear mode growth).
    gresho        [A]  Gresho-Chan steady rotating vortex.
    sedov         [A]  Sedov-Taylor point-blast wave.
    noh           [A]  Noh implosion (strong converging radial shock).
    evrard        [A]  Evrard adiabatic spherical collapse.
    polytrope     [A]  Self-gravitating polytrope / Lane-Emden (needs relaxation).
    blob          [A]  Cloud-crushing blob in a supersonic wind.
    areablob           Hydrostatic blob(s) in a uniform medium.
    taylorgreen   [A]  Taylor-Green vortex (viscous decay).
    square        [A]  Hydrostatic square (Saitoh-Makino surface-tension test).
    isentropicvortex [A]  Yee isentropic vortex advection (convergence).
    rt            [A]  Rayleigh-Taylor instability.
    shocktube     [A]  Riemann shock-tube suite (hydro + MHD presets).
    coldkeplerian [A]  Cold Keplerian disk/ring (AV / angular-momentum test).
    accdisk            Accretion disk.
    planet             Planet / planet-in-disk simulation.
    planetcollision    Planet collision.

  Cosmology:
    zeldovich     [A]  Zeldovich pancake (collapse to a caustic).
    cosmowave     [A]  Cosmological (M)HD waves in an expanding (EdS) universe.

  Linear waves:
    wave          [A]  Linear (M)HD wave convergence (Stone et al.).

  Magnetohydrodynamics:
    alfven        [A]  Circularly-polarized Alfven wave (convergence).
    orzag         [A]  Orszag-Tang vortex (2-D / 3-D).
    mhdrotor      [A]  Balsara-Spicer MHD rotor.
    mhdloop       [A]  Field-loop advection (Gardiner & Stone).
    mhdloopshear       Sheared field-loop advection variant.
    mhdcollapse   [A]  Magnetized rotating-cloud collapse (Wissing & Shen).
    mhddivtest    [A]  Hyperbolic divergence-cleaning test (Tricco & Price).
    mhdisowave    [A]  Isolated longitudinal MHD/sound pulse (Iwasaki).
    currentsheet  [A]  2-D MHD current sheet / reconnection.
    mti           [A]  Magnetothermal instability (Owens et al.).
    mhdbalsaravortex   Balsara MHD vortex.
    mri                Magnetorotational instability.

Analysis
--------

Each simulation with an [A] above has a post-processing script
setupfiles/IC_analysis_<name>.py that reads a run's snapshots and compares them
against that test's analytic / reference solution. The scripts share one CLI, so
every test is analysed the same way.

You declare the run the SAME way you launched it: the analysis takes the same
-a..-h parameters, with the same defaults, as that test's setup in runtest.sh
(no sidecar file -- the physics is derived from the parameters you pass).

Basic usage (point it at the run directory produced by runtest.sh):
  python setupfiles/IC_analysis_<name>.py <run-dir> [-a .. -h ..] [--save out]

  --save out            write figures to out_*.png instead of showing them
  --times t [t ..]      comparison time(s) (one profile panel each; default is
                        test-specific, often the last snapshot). A single value
                        is just --times <t>.
  --labels L1 L2 ..     legend labels when several runs are overlaid
  --no-analytic         drop the analytic overlay

The analytic (or tabulated reference) solution is ALWAYS overlaid and the error
metric (an L1 / residual) is printed.

Reference / regression workflow (lock in a result, then detect changes):
  1. Bless a baseline for a run, either via runtest:
         ./runtest.sh -r <name> <Nsmooth> <Nres> <type>
     or directly:
         python setupfiles/IC_analysis_<name>.py <run-dir> --save-reference
     This writes <run-parent>/references/<runname>/ holding reference.json (the
     metric series), render_<field>_*.npz (field-map baselines) and a copy of the
     run .log. Use --save-reference-all to bless the render grids at EVERY dump
     (needed for reference movies).
  2. Compare a later run against it:
         python setupfiles/IC_analysis_<name>.py <run-dir> --reference
     --reference (opt-in) auto-discovers the run's own references/<runname>/,
     overlays the blessed curve on every plot, and prints the residuals; pass a
     folder or .json to compare against a DIFFERENT run's baseline. Add
         --reg-tol 1e-6
     to turn it into a CI gate (non-zero exit if the worst residual exceeds the
     tolerance).

Field-map rendering and movies:
  --render              render 2-D field maps at selected snapshots
  --render-times t ..   which snapshots to render (separate from --times;
                        default: --render-n evenly spaced)
  --render-backend B    grid (default, pynbody-free), grid-petkova, pynbody,
                        hist, or particles
  --render-project P    slice | column | rhocolumn | average
  --render-extent X0 X1 Y0 Y1, --render-res R, --render-aspect, --render-rows, ...
  --movie               animate each field map over ALL snapshots (mp4 via
                        ffmpeg, else gif); combine with --reference for a
                        sim | reference | difference movie
  --residual            residual render grids (implies --render):
                        with ONE run + --reference, draws
                        sim | reference | (sim - reference) panels from the
                        blessed render grids; with TWO runs (no reference
                        needed), draws run1 | run2 | (run1 - run2),
                        differencing the runs directly on the same grid.
                        More than two runs is an error.

Convergence (tests that support it -- alfven, gresho, wave, isentropicvortex,
coldkeplerian, mhdisowave): pass several runs at different resolutions plus
--convergence to plot the error vs n_x against the ideal n_x^-2 line, e.g.
  python setupfiles/IC_analysis_gresho.py <dir_N32> <dir_N64> <dir_N128> --convergence

Continuous integration (regression-gating a code)
--------------------------------------------------

The bless / --reference / --reg-tol workflow above is what lets an SPH code wire
this testsuite into its own CI: every change to the code is automatically
validated by re-running a small, low-resolution subset of the tests and gating
on the blessed metrics. The pattern is code-agnostic (gasoline / ChaNGa /
SPH-EXA -- anything runtest.sh can drive):

  1. Pick a cheap matrix: a few tests at low Nsmooth/Nres on a lattice, e.g.
         sedov 32 16 0      orzag 32 16 0
  2. Bless once, with the EXACT build + config CI will later use (same flags,
     same resolution, same particle-distribution), so the baseline matches what
     the gate runs:
         ./runtest.sh -r sedov 32 16 0
     This commits test_cases/<test>/references/<runname>/ into the repo.
  3. On each code change, rebuild, re-run the same rows, and gate:
         ./runtest.sh sedov 32 16 0
         python setupfiles/IC_analysis_sedov.py <run-dir> --reference --reg-tol 1e-1
     A non-zero exit (worst residual over tolerance) fails the build. Use one
     analysis step PER test so the CI UI shows a separate pass/fail per case.

Keep reg-tol loose at low resolution (1e-1 is typical) -- it catches gross
regressions without flagging run-to-run noise; tighten it for higher-resolution
or deterministic tests.

A complete worked example for the ChaNGa fork (self-contained GitHub Actions
workflow, the curated matrix, and a local build+bless helper) lives under ci/ --
see ci/CHANGA_CICD_PLAN.md. Note: the GitHub workflow itself must live in the
code's OWN repo (.github/workflows/), since Actions only runs workflows from the
repo under test; this testsuite supplies the tests, analysis, and committed
references that the workflow pulls in.

Resampling an IC: splitting / merging particles
-----------------------------------------------

To change the particle count of an existing tipsy snapshot (and all its aux
fields -- BField, iord, ...) without regenerating a glass from scratch, use the
glassresample tool. Splitting raises resolution (one particle -> N children,
mass and extensive quantities like u/B divided among them); merging lowers it
(N particles -> 1, quantities summed/averaged):

  icgenerator/glassgen_python/glassresample <tipsy.NNNNN> [options]

  glassresample pre.00000 --op split --factor 8        # 8x more particles
  glassresample fine.00000 --op merge --factor 8 -o coarse

The box (needed for periodic wrapping) and output name default from the input:
it reads <input>.param if present and writes <input>_<op>.00000 plus re-emitted
aux files with the new count. Override with --param / --box LX LY LZ / --open
and -o. Run `glassresample --help` for the full option list (--dist, --margin,
-s, ...). A split/merge is geometric only -- for a clean glass at the new count,
relax the result afterwards (the relaxation path, runtest.sh type 2 / glassrelax).

Interpolating a snapshot onto a grid or mesh
--------------------------------------------

To resample an SPH snapshot from particles onto a structured target (e.g. to
hand off to a grid code, or for visualisation/analysis) use the sph_interp
package via its wrapper:

  ./interpolate_to_grid.sh INPUT OUTPUT [options]
  ./interpolate_to_grid.sh              # no args -> interactive prompts

  TARGETS (--grid):          uniform | amr | voronoi | projection
  METHODS (--method):        petkova (exact, mass-conserving; default) | sph
                             (fast, approximate)
  OUTPUT (--output-format):  npz | hdf5 | ramses | cell-table | native

Examples:
  # 256^3 uniform SPH density grid -> npz
  ./interpolate_to_grid.sh run/snap.00100 rho.npz --grid uniform --npx 256

  # mass-conserving AMR octree of rho+velocity, exported as RAMSES HDF5
  ./interpolate_to_grid.sh run/snap.00100 mesh.h5 --grid amr --method petkova \
      --fields rho,vx,vy,vz --output-format ramses

  # xy column-density projection map
  ./interpolate_to_grid.sh run/snap.00100 col.npz --grid projection \
      --axes xy --project column

To see every target geometry rendered side by side on one snapshot, run
  ./interp_demo.sh [SNAPSHOT]

Converting between tipsy and SPH-EXA
------------------------------------

tipsy -> SPH-EXA (convert an IC for an SPH-EXA run):
  python setupfiles/ICconvert_tipsytosphexa.py <tipsy-IC> <output>
Writes <output>.h5 (SPH-EXA Step#0 layout). The matching <name>.param must sit
next to the IC (box, gamma, EOS, gravity are read from it); a non-zero
.BFieldx/y/z aux makes it an MHD datafile (magneto::* fields).

SPH-EXA -> tipsy (convert a finished SPH-EXA run for analysis):
  python setupfiles/ICconvert_sphexatotipsy.py <run.h5> <runname> <idx_interval>
Writes tipsy snapshots <runname>/<runname>.<idx> (idx = (N+1)*idx_interval;
pick the interval to match the gasoline numbering, e.g. 10 -> .00010, .00020),
the B-field/divB aux (.BFieldx/y/z, .DivB), and converts constants.txt (cwd or
<runname>/) into a gasoline-style .log with the box in the header.
